 Automatic Typo Correction

 The Elysium Enigma incorporates Steve Breslin's Spelling Corrector
 extension, which can correct some typos for you.  For example, if you
 type:


 Then, depending on context, the game may be able to correct this to:


 And proceed to execute the appropriate command.  This can be very
 useful in correcting minor errors automatically, rather than
 presenting you with a parser error and the need to retype a command,
 but there are two things you should note about this feature:

 (1) This library extension (rightly) takes a conservative approach to
 typo-correction, making only those corrections that are very likely to
 be correct, rather than risking speculative corrections that were not
 what the player intended.  This means that you may often find that the
 game does not correct a typo that looks obvious to you.  In such a
 case the reason is probably that the correction was not so obvious to
 the algorithm used by the spelling corrector; it's far better not to
 have the game "correct" your input to something you didn't intend and
 execute a command you didn't want.

 (2) For this reason, no automatic typo correction occurs in
 conversational commands (like ASK and TELL) and other such commands
 where any input is potentially valid.  For example, you can ask an NPC
 about anything you like, so it would be highly annoying to have:


 "corrected" to:


 Which might happen if "move" but not "love" is one of the words
 defined in the game's dictionary.

 (3) Should you find this typo-correction feature more of a hindrance
 than a help you can disable it with the TYPO OFF command.  Use TYPO ON
 command to turn it back on (you can also use the bare TYPO command to
 toggle the two states).

 [The End]
