 Abort on/off (for multiple commands)

 Sometimes when you enter multiple commands on a single command line,
 the failure of one of the earlier commands renders the subsequent ones
 problematic or at least redundant.  For example, suppose there's a
 troll who won't let you go north, but you enter two NORTH commands in
 succession:


 The ugly troll blocks your path with a growl.

 The ugly troll blocks your path with a growl.

 The second message is really superfluous, since you probably didn't
 mean to try to go north twice from your present location, but rather
 to go north then go north again.

 In other situations, this could be even more troubling.  Suppose you
 enter a command line like:


 If the first command fails, but travel east from your current location
 is possible, you could end up doing something quite different from
 what you intended.

 To avoid this problem The Elysium Enigma cancels any subsequent
 commands on a command line if one of the commands fails.  It does not
 however cancel the iteration of a command.  So, for example, if you
 entered the command:


 And DROP TROUSERS failed halfway through the list of items to be
 dropped ("You'd better not drop your trousers in public!"), the DROP
 command would continue through the list of other items that might be
 dropped, but the NORTH command would be cancelled (since a previous
 command had failed).

 In most cases this behaviour will probably give better results than
 the normal library behaviour, but if you don't like it you can turn it
 off with the ABORT OFF command; all commands on the command line will
 then be executed even if one fails.  You can also turn it on again
 with an ABORT ON command, or toggle between settings with a simple
 ABORT command.

 [The End]








