 "There, sir," the shuttle pilot points to a tiny collection of
 buildings nestling next to the river, "That's the town."

 "That's the town!" you cry, "Are you sure, sublieutenant?"

 "Quite sure, sir," the pilot assures you as she checks her
 navigational instruments, "Which means our designated landing zone
 should be just the other side of that forest."

 You let out a deep sigh as the shuttle carries out its final descent
 over the farmland and turns to sweep over the multi-coloured trees.
 It's not that you have any objection to walking per se, indeed the
 prospect of a good brisk walk on a sunny morning is rather appealing
 after four days cooped up in a frigate; it's being obliged to walk to
 this meeting just to avoid upsetting the natives' technophobic
 sensibilities that irritates you.

 The pilot now has the shuttle under manual control; she kills the
 speed and drops the craft into a hollow just north of the forest.  As
 she finally cuts the engines she turns to you with a brisk smile.
 "Right, here we are, sir," she announces cheerfully.  Pointing to the
 south she adds, "The town should be about a quarter of an hour's walk
 that way.  I think I spotted a path running more or less straight
 through the forest, so you shouldn't have any difficulty finding it."

 "Thanks," you reply laconically.  You let out another sigh; but at
 least this shouldn't take more than a couple of hours, then you'll be
 away from this wretched backwater - hopefully for good.

 Inside the Shuttle (sitting on the passenger seat)
 The inside of the shuttle is not exactly spacious; there's room for
 the pilot and three passengers, one beside the pilot and two behind.
 The seats are comfortable enough, but otherwise it's all pretty basic.
 There's not much in front of you except the forward window; the pilot
 has a bank of instruments.

 The pilot is sitting next to you; she's turned to face you, as if
 waiting for you to speak.

>typo off
 Typo correction disabled.

>ask pilot about town
 "What do you know about this place?" you ask her.

 "Only what I've heard, sir," she replies, "I've never been here
 before.  It does have quite an odd reputation, though, as I'm sure you
 know.  Something went horribly wrong in the past, but no-one wants to
 talk about it.  And now the natives refuse to use any technology
 that's much more advanced than the wheel."

>ask pilot about natives
 As you start your question the pilot lets out a wide yawn.

>ask pilot about mission
 "So, sublieutenant, what do you think about..." you begin.

 "Perhaps we should discuss that some other time, sir," the pilot
 suggests, "right now you have a job to do."

>ask pilot about meeting
 "About meetings..." you begin.

 "What about meetings, sir?" she replies warily.

 "Well..." you start, but something in her manner makes you trail off
 as you realize your question wasn't all that important after all.

>inventory
 You are carrying nothing, and are wearing a purple belt and a white
 uniform.  The purple belt contains a drik.  Your left pocket contains
 an ID card.  Your right pocket contains a crumpled piece of paper.

>read paper
 (first taking the crumpled piece of paper from your right pocket)
 After the standard preamble, it goes on:

 "I'm sorry to dump this on you, but the Federation crisis means that
 we've had to pull all but skeleton resources out of this sector, and
 you're the nearest Legion officer to hand.  As a result, we need you
 to include Elysium in your rounds.  It's a sensitive planet - probably
 one of the most sensitive settlements in the Empire - but provided you
 go straight in and straight out and stick strictly to these orders you
 shouldn't have any problems.

 The purpose of your visit is simply to remind the local leadership
 that they are still part of the Empire and that we are still keeping
 tabs on them; quite literally, you're just there to 'show the flag'.
 To do this you'll need to make your way to the Legion office in what
 passes for the settlement's capital, and, once there, hoist the
 imperial flag above the building to show the local Elders that you're
 open for business.  One or more of them should then come to call on
 you within the hour.  When they do, be as diplomatic and courteous as
 possible, but otherwise keep the conversation to a minimum.  Inform
 them in the simplest possible terms of the nature of the Federation
 crisis, emphasising that the Empire will continue to guard them from
 intrusion. Ask them if they have anything they want to raise with you.
 Almost certainly they won't, apart from their standard grumbles about
 imperial interference.  Say as little as possible in reply beyond
 promising to pass their comments on.  Once you have completed this
 conversation get out of there as quickly as you can.

 The most important thing to understand about the Elysians is that they
 have made a religion of technophobia.  Their idea of a paradisal
 society is a pre-industrial society, so try not to flaunt any
 technology you bring with you; the less the settlers see of any
 thirtieth-century technology, the better you'll get on with them.

 Finally, I cannot stress too strongly that you should on no account
 get involved in any of the internal affairs of Elysium, and that you
 should if at all possible avoid any contact with any of the settlers
 apart from the Elders who come to meet you.  Terrible mistakes have
 been made on Elysium in the past, and any problems that come up in the
 present must be left to officers with a deep understanding of the
 situation there, which does not include you.  So, get in, keep the
 chat nice and short, and get straight out again.

 I look forward to receiving your report in due course.
 Subtribune G.F.  Booker (C/O Sect PP12, ISL)
 13-Sep-2980.

 [Auth Code: ISL-GF-PPn342]"

